headline: Michael Dell on Invest America, His $6.25 Billion Bet on Investing for Children, and AI’s Breakthrough Year
summary: Michael Dell, founder and CEO of Dell Technologies and one of the most influential figures in tech, speaks with WSJ Leadership Institute President Alan Murray in Davos about why he became involved in Invest America—investment accounts for children—and why he and his wife, Susan Dell, donated $6.25 billion to help kick-start the initiative. Dell also discusses AI and why he believes 2026 will be a “breakthrough” year for the technology.

headline: Apple and Dell supplier Pegatron expects US plant to be completed by end-March
summary: Taiwanese contract electronics manufacturer Pegatron's first U.S. factory, in Texas, is expected to ​be completed by the end of March, with trial ‌production to begin around then or April, President and CEO Kuang-Chih Cheng ‌said on Friday.  The company, a supplier to Apple and Dell, said in October that it had acquired an industrial building and land in Texas, joining other Taiwan tech manufacturers investing ⁠in the state including ‌Foxconn, Inventec and Wistron.  "It is currently scheduled to be completed by the end of March, and we should be ​able to begin trial production in late March or April."
